Your task is to write a Jest test case that exposes a specific mutation in a JavaScript/TypeScript project.

MUTATION DETAILS
The mutation affects the following file:
sinks/drain.js
Here is the full content of that file (shown with a <PLACEHOLDER> marker):
'use strict'

module.exports = function drain (op, done) {
  var read, abort

  // Declared here so that it captures the drain's stack trace
  var doneLackingErr
  if (!done) {
    doneLackingErr = new Error('no done callback supplied')
  }

  function sink (_read) {
    read = _read
    if(abort) return sink.abort()
    //this function is much simpler to write if you
    //just use recursion, but by using a while loop
    //we do not blow the stack if the stream happens to be sync.
    ;(function next() {
        var loop = true, cbed = false
        while(loop) {
          cbed = false
          read(null, function (end, data) {
            cbed = true
            if(end = end || abort) {
              loop = false
              if(done) done(end === true ? null : end)
                 <PLACEHOLDER>

                console.warn(doneLackingErr)
                throw end
              }
            }
            else if(op && false === op(data) || abort) {
              loop = false
              read(abort || true, done || function () {})
            }
            else if(!loop){
              next()
            }
          })
          if(!cbed) {
            loop = false
            return
          }
        }
      })()
  }

  sink.abort = function (err, cb) {
    if('function' == typeof err)
      cb = err, err = true
    abort = err || true
    if(read) return read(abort, cb || function () {})
  }

  return sink
}

In the original code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

-                 else if(end && end !== true) {
In the mutated code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

+                 else if(end && end !== false) {


YOUR TASK
Write one Jest test file that:
    1. Passes when run against the original code.
    2. Fails when run against the mutated code.
    3. Tests the behavior of the mutated file in a way that reliably detects the mutation.
The test will be saved at the following path, relative to this test-generation project’s root:
llm-cache/anthropic_claude-sonnet-4.6/temp_0.5/withoutTests/cached/artifacts/pull-stream/attempt_1/pending_category/mutant-919acb6/testCase.test.ts

ALLOWED LIBRARIES
You may use:
    1. Any built-in Node.js modules (e.g., fs, path, crypto, etc.).

You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the change is:
- Original: `else if(end && end !== true)`
- Mutated: `else if(end && end !== false)`

This affects the behavior when `end` is `true` (normal stream end). In the original code, when `end === true`, the condition `end !== true` is `false`, so the `else if` branch is NOT taken. In the mutated code, when `end === true`, the condition `end !== false` is `true`, so the `else if` branch IS taken (which calls `console.warn` and throws the error).

So the mutation causes the code to throw an error when a stream ends normally (with `end === true`) and there's no `done` callback provided.

I need to write a test that:
1. Creates a stream that ends normally (with `true`)
2. Does NOT provide a `done` callback
3. In the original code, this should work without throwing
4. In the mutated code, this will throw because `end !== false` is `true` when `end === true`

Wait, let me re-read. When `done` is provided, the `if(done)` branch runs and returns. The `else if` only runs when `done` is falsy. So the test needs to have no `done` callback and a stream that ends normally.

```typescript
import drain from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/sinks/drain.js";

describe("drain sink", () => {
  it("should not throw when stream ends normally (end === true) without a done callback", () => {
    // Create a simple source that immediately ends
    let callCount = 0;
    const source = (end: any, cb: (end: any, data?: any) => void) => {
      if (end) {
        cb(end);
        return;
      }
      callCount++;
      if (callCount === 1) {
        cb(null, "data");
      } else {
        cb(true); // normal end
      }
    };

    // Without a done callback - in original code this should not throw on normal end
    // In mutated code, it will throw because end===true satisfies `end !== false`
    expect(() => {
      const sink = drain(null); // no done callback
      sink(source);
    }).not.toThrow();
  });
});
```

